b'We asked 4 artists to share their interpretation of Latinx/Hispanic Heritage Month. Here\'s what @cristalgutierrezart came up with:\n\n"Color is beautiful. As a Latinx artist, I always look to my cultural roots for inspiration. And one of the things I find most beautiful about my culture is the use of vibrant colors. I love going to Mexican markets and seeing colorful papel picado or playful pi\xc3\xb1atas hanging from the ceiling. I love the lively murals that adorn the flower markets and food trucks near my house. I love the colorful ribbons and vivid patterns that form the aesthetic of Folklorico dancers. The loud colors proudly exclaim, \'I am here!\' Which is why my illustrations are often full of color. It is one of the ways I like to pay homage to my heritage. A way to illustrate confidence, strength, and pride. I want the womxn in my illustrations to exclaim, \'I am here!\' Color is beautiful and I chose to embrace it. Whether I\xe2\x80\x99m using it for my art or on my lips to accentuate my hoops, it serves as a reminder that we hail from colorful roots full of history and resilience. AND, in another sense, color is beautiful because we are all unique and there is no single definition of beauty. Be proud of your color. Embrace it and take up space as you proudly exclaim, \'I AM HERE!"'

b'We asked artists to share their interpretation of Latinx/Hispanic Heritage Month. Here's what @habito.cr came up with:

"Hola! Mi nombre es Beatriz Castro, Soy bailarina, disen\xcc\x83adora e ilustradora nacida en Costa Rica. Costa Rica es un pai\xcc\x81s muy pequen\xcc\x83o en medio de America. Somos conocides mundialmente por ser el pai\xcc\x81s ma\xcc\x81s feliz del mundo. Realmente no se\xcc\x81 que\xcc\x81 tan cierto sera\xcc\x81 eso, pero si\xcc\x81 se\xcc\x81 que somos personas de almas hermosas. Fuimos criades para ser solidaries con las personas, para dar al que no tiene. Y pensa\xcc\x81ndolo bien, creo que esta es la mejor manera de describir lo que significa ser latine, somos una comunidad de personas, conectadas por culturas e historias similares. Luchamos las mismas luchas y sufrimos las mismas injusticias. Como mujer latina siento las almas de todes dentro de mi\xcc\x81, somos familia, juntes celebramos y juntes luchamos. Nuestra belleza no tiene li\xcc\x81mites, tampoco puede ser categorizada en algu\xcc\x81n estereotipo. Ser latina es una responsabilidad  al igual que un privilegio. 

"Hello! My name is Beatriz Castro, I'm a dancer, designer and illustrator from Costa Rica. Costa Rica is a really small country in the middle of America, the continent. We are known worldwide for being the happiest people on earth. I don't know if that's exactly true, but we do have really beautiful souls, we were raised to be in solidarity with others, to give to those who have not. And I think that's the best way to describe what being Latin is, we are a community of people connected by our similar culture, our similar histories. We fight the same fights; we suffer the same injustices.  As a Latina woman I can feel all of our souls connected, we are all relatives, we celebrate for all and we fight for all. Our beauty has no limits, nor can it be categorized into a stereotype. Being Latina is a responsibility and also a privilege."'

b'For #LatinxHeritageMonth, we asked 5 Latinx artists to share their interpretation of the month. Here's what @chantelsanchez_ came up with: 

"What is the most beautiful part of your Latinx culture? What makes you proud to be Latinx? What is something about your culture you wish people understood? These are the questions I contemplated while working on this illustration. Latinx people are beautiful because of their diversity. We tend to get lumped into being Mexican as the default. Latinx people are from many different countries, each with distinct food, culture, and language. I wish people understood that Latinx people are Black, Asian, White, Indigenous, etc. We don't all look the same but that is beautiful. We are all different but united.
For my illustration, I was inspired by traditional Mexican embroidery that is full of colorful floral patterns. I drew different flowers to symbolize the diversity in the Latinx culture. I also decided to hand letter the phrase in Spanish and English because that is a significant part of my culture having grown up bilingual."'

b'For #NationalLipstickDay, we asked 5 Black artists to share their interpretation of the day. Here's what they came up with:

The Story of \xe2\x80\x9cCoco Queen\xe2\x80\x9d by Shonte Young Williams (@shonteyoungwilliams)

The bell chimes overhead as she steps through the glass door into "Malcolm's" deli. Covering her phone with her hand, she approaches the counter. "Can I have a turkey and cheese, Mr. Malcom?" 

"Of course, changing things up, I see," he jokes, reaching into the display case for the honey roasted turkey she ordered EVERY day. 

"Thanks, Mr. Malcom," she said, returning his easy smile. 

Replacing the phone to her ear, she continues her conversation. 

"Ok, D I just ordered, wassup?" 

"Girl, me and Aisha are coming to scoop you, there's an Ice Cream Festival at Benton Park." 

"I just got back to the neighborhood, she groans, and I gotta ask my mom if I can go." 

"Girl, we coming right now!" D shouts with finality. 

"Ok, ok, see you!" 

 Checking herself out in the glass, 

(yea, I'm still cute!), 

 she realizes her CRUCIAL mistake. She snaps her pocketbook open, revealing her gum, bus pass, and of course, her favorite purple lipstick. 

"See you tomorrow, Mr. Malcom," she calls happily as she grabs her sandwich and hurries out the door. 

#shareblackstories'

b'For #NationalLipstickDay, we asked 5 Black artists to share their interpretation of the day. Here's what they came up with:

"Mother's Lipstick" by Mawhyah Milton (@mawhyah)

"I used to watch my mother when she put on her lipstick. It was always a passionate bright red and made her look like a movie star. 

I remember once asking her if I could wear some. She looked down at me and said "only a little". 

She bent down and gave me a peck on the lips. 

I rushed to the mirror rubbing my lips together like I saw her do multiple times. 

The gag is, literally zero lipstick transferred to my lips but I pretended it did and pretended all day. 

Now when I wear lipstick, I experiment wearing all sorts of colors because I can't pick a favorite. 

I use poppy flowers in this illustration to symbolize the loss of my mother. 

Things I remember, like what perfume she wore or me watching her apply lipstick will always be a fond memory."'

b'#Regram @theouai Detox Shampoo & Scalp & Body Scrub: When to use one, the other, or both? 
If you want to exfoliate your scalp - use Scalp and Body Scrub. The sugar crystals will gently exfoliate and help calm dryness and itchiness, but it won\xe2\x80\x99t cleanse like our Detox Shampoo will. 
If you want a cleanse - use Detox Shampoo. The apple cider vinegar is going to work the hardest at getting rid of heavy buildup on your hair and scalp so that it feels totally refreshed and renewed.

If you want to exfoliate AND cleanse - Use both! Use them together, or use the scrub first and Detox second. Your hair will be left feeling clean, detoxed, refreshed, hydrated and moisturized. You may have combo hair, just like you have combo skin, so feel free to experiment to find what works for you.'

b"#Regram @deciem The Ordinary\xe2\x80\x99s Niacinamide 10% + Zinc 1% has always been one of our most well-loved products (so much so that we recently launched it in a cuddlier, larger 60ml format for die-hard fans of the formula). \xe2\x81\xa3:test_tube: \xe2\x81\xa3\xe2\x81\xa3\xe2\x81\xa3\xe2\x81\xa0
\xe2\x81\xa3\xe2\x81\xa3\xe2\x81\xa0
Niacinamide, also known as Vitamin B3, is a high-strength vitamin and mineral formula that helps to support barrier function, while reducing the appearance of visible shine and signs of congestion. This ingredient has also been shown to have a brightening effect on the skin, making it a truly multifunctional ingredient that can be easily incorporated into any routine. We have included Niacinamide at a high 10% concentration within this formula. \xe2\x81\xa3\xe2\x81\xa3\xe2\x81\xa3\xe2\x81\xa0
\xe2\x81\xa3\xe2\x81\xa3\xe2\x81\xa3\xe2\x81\xa0
Additionally, this formula includes a 1% concentration of Zinc PCA, which works to support the skin's function as a protective barrier. \xe2\x81\xa3:umbrella_selector:\xe2\x81\xa3\xe2\x81\xa3\xe2\x81\xa0
\xe2\x81\xa3\xe2\x81\xa3\xe2\x81\xa3\xe2\x81\xa0
Niacinamide can be applied in the AM and PM alongside other water-based serums, before oils and creams. We do not recommend applying Niacinamide in the same routine as pure Vitamin C as Niacinamide has the capacity to affect the integrity of Vitamin C, potentially reducing its efficacy. If you\xe2\x80\x99d like to incorporate Niacinamide and Vitamin C into your routine, we would suggest applying them at separate times. \xe2\x81\xa3:sun_selector::crescent_moon:\xe2\x81\xa3\xe2\x81\xa3\xe2\x81\xa0
\xe2\x81\xa3\xe2\x81\xa3\xe2\x81\xa3\xe2\x81\xa0"

b"Curl friends: This one's for you :backhand_index_pointing_up:
While you're stuck inside, show your hair a little extra love. Watch Ulta Beauty Collective member, @itstayloranne__ , share this deep conditioning hack she picked up from @_aubreanascurlss for when you don't have access to a hooded dryer. 
1. Apply treatment and put your hair under a plastic cap.
2. Grab a pair of leggings and tie a knot on one side.
3. Secure the leggings on your head and grab your blow dryer. Stick the blow dryer into the untied side of the leggings and you will feel the hot air on your head.
4. Do this for 10-20 mins.
